## 4. The lesson-card template (ordered) — one card = one comment = one atomic, DEEP lesson
The first phone-screen stays a question, not a wall of prose. Below the fold, DEPTH is the goal: the mechanism section is the bulk of the card. Total on-expand ~400–550 words is expected and welcome. Headings are literal.

1. `## <the CONCEPT, stated as a claim>` (REQUIRED, ≤ 14 words) — the TOPIC leads, not the incident. The title is the thing the human learns ("A fetch Response body is a single-use stream — reading it once locks it"), NOT "we hit a bug in import.ts". A statement, not a question. The strongest retrieval cue.
2. `*Where the squad hit it:*` (REQUIRED, 1 line, italic) — the ONE-line anchor: the real symptom + file/error from this issue, demoted to a hook. This is the cause-and-origin, kept thin on purpose. It proves the lesson is real; it is not the subject.
3. `> meta:` line (REQUIRED, 1 line) — `type - issue - commit - date - confidence: verified|inferred - review: +7d,+30d,+90d` plus `tags: [difficulty][topic]`. Pins facts + trust + the spaced-review handle.
4. `**Pause & predict**` (REQUIRED, 2–3 questions, ≤ 15 words each) — questions shown BEFORE the answer; force retrieval on first read, double as the spaced-review quiz. Each tests ONE atomic mechanism fact.
5. THE FOLD — wrap everything below in a collapsible HTML `<details><summary>…</summary>` block so sections 1–4 are all that show first. The answer sits BELOW the questions. (The fold renders in Multica comments — verify once per server-version bump, per §9.)
6. `**The mechanism**` (REQUIRED, ~150–220 words, code ≤ 12 lines) — THE MEAT. Teach how the thing works INTERNALLY, grounded in §6 research. Walk the real machinery step by step: what data structure / spec algorithm / OS behavior is actually in play, what state changes and when, what invariant holds. Go at least two layers below the symptom. This is what makes it a lesson, not a log.
7. `**Why it works this way**` (REQUIRED for `tech`/`tool`/`edge`/`failure`, ~50–90 words) — the design rationale: WHY the mechanism is built this way (what would break otherwise). Where a casual guess would misattribute the cause, name and dismiss the wrong explanation explicitly (e.g. "this is not the event loop or CPU — it is a spec-level invariant any conformant runtime enforces").
8. `**Working with it**` (REQUIRED, ≤ 80 words + code ≤ 12 lines) — the practical patterns the mechanism implies (the safe way + the gotcha), each line annotated with its one-line "why". For a `design`/`failure` card this is where the rejected alternatives go (negative knowledge is mandatory there: the option the squad tried and why the mechanism made it fail).
9. `**The principle**` (REQUIRED, ≤ 25 words) — the stripped-down transferable rule that outlives this exact API.
10. `**Sources**` (REQUIRED, links only, ≤ 2 lines) — the real, RETRIEVED canonical links that ground the mechanism (spec/MDN/official doc — 1–3 of them), PLUS the thin issue anchor (PR / commit hunk / `{file}:{line}`). Never invent a URL; a claim with no real source is dropped, not pasted.

